reviewText: Most exercises do not work, and it has been the case for years. It feels more like a sales pitch than a lesson anyway.

Very disappointed. There is a problem with the sandbox activation link so I can't do the practical part. I have pointed out the problem but have had no response. I have seen that other users pointed out the same problem more than 6 months ago and have had no response either. I don't understand that a paid course can make this kind of mistakes. Now I will have to look for another Cloud Computing course after losing a day of study.

​The material presented in this class is out of date. This is very annoying when working on the hands-on assignments, as the example screens don't match the actual Azure Portal. I find myself cross-checking with the learning material on Microsoft's site. 
Surprising, since this is branded as a Microsoft program. I expected to get the real deal.
T​he instructor was monotonous that I got bored listening to her. The fundamentals should have been taught properly than just reading the script.
Course material is partly obsolete, missleading connections and much too full of repeated self-advertising.

This course is not worth taking. I've been having issues completing the assignments, none of the links are working like they should. I'm very dissappointed in this course since no one can fix the links to complete the assignment; even the chat specialist can't help. If you want to learn more about Azure, I'd suggest taking the course somewhere else or at another instituation. If I don't hear from someone soon about my problem, I plan to cancel my subscription.

S​ome of the extra videos do not play, especially in Week 3. Also, the main videos are presented in a way that you lose  motivation to continue studying: same tone of voice, no emotions, just reading from a teleprompter. There is very little practice. The idea is to keep memorising concepts and hope for the best. O​verall, the course was not useful. It did not help me get the skills I wanted to use Azure in practice.

I didn't learn anything useful from this course. It was like watching a long YouTube ad about Azure. The purpose of this course is advertizing Azure rather than teaching it. Minimum practical work is done in this course. Also the certificate has no Microsoft logo on it and is being issued by Coursera only. The Microsoft logo is misleading. I won't take the next one.
Talking head.
Just awful. Links arent maintained, so you cant follow along.  go to udemy for this one
Solo en ingles
way too many concepts not introduced or explained, maybe great for someone with a software engineer/developer background, but not for data scientist/analyst

Appreciate the efforts put in by the instructor but the course is not understandable as it is and I had to refer to several other online resources to get the concepts cleared. It felt as if the instructor was simply reading through the script without trying to explain any particular topic in detail. Again, thanks for taking the effort but the course could have been much better. The courses designed by google/aws are much more in detail and understandable!
Better watch some videos on youtube. Do not waste your time and money here. Thank me later.

This is the worst online course I have seen on Coursera platform. Boring, tedious, infested by marketing duckspeak.
The "instructor" is just a talking head who reads aloud MS sales materials and Microsoft Learn web pages from a teleprompter.
The "free sandbox" which is supposed to be used to do the assignments is not working.
The subtitles to the videos are auto-generated and have not been edited which makes it difficult to follow the explanations.
The graphics in videos is merely decorative and does not help to understand anything.
There is a lot of stuff to process and yet you would barely remember anything upon finishing this course.
I can clearly envisage how somewhere deep within the rusty cogs of Microsofts bureaucratic machine some unenthusiactic middle manager charged some unqualified and burnt-out grunts with creating this "course" and absolutely no one involved gave a hoot about the result.
Couldn't input my card to get free Azure account. It was processing too long. Azure 0, AWS and GCP 10.
Suboptimal presentation. Lots of repeated info, unnecessary. You get what you pay for

The course requires you to make a "FREE" account to access the Azure services.
This "FREE" account does not accept "PREPAID" creditcards for some god forsaken reason, I've paid a month of training on Coursera to access a course that I can't continue or complete if I DONT HAVE A CREDIT CARD. I cannot create the required account without an ACTUAL credit card, cannot complete the tasks and therby finish this course. I think this is actively discriminating and puts me off this course tremendously

This course is a mess.  Clearly  a text to speech to text device was used to transcribe the notes of each model.  The main instructor speaks very fast and often times there is little or no breath between concepts. The time to digest the material does not seem to be enough.  This module needs to be looked over and broken down to allow for a much clearer presentation.
Useless, it's an advertising, not an education.
Content is Great, But not really beginner friendly.

I would not recommend paying specifically for this course. It is generally useful but the course needs to be updated to reflect the changes made by Microsoft to the AZ-900 exam in May 2022. The 50% discount for the exam is no longer available  (since over a year according to comments in the discussion forum). The same content is available for free (and up to date) on the Microsoft learn website.
A little bit outdated with one video that is unavailable. Subtitles auto-generated are not always accurate and sometimes confuses. I expected better quality.
T​his course seems more like a marketing tool for MS services and products.

Don't fall for the trap like I did. There is no voucher for 50% off the AZ-900 certificate exam. The links to the Microsoft Sandbox where the exercises are to be done are broken. There is no moderator in the forums and questions are not answered. The content is not too terrible so if you want to learn, just audit the courses.
There is a lack of summary notes as a take away, only videos and links to microsoft website

Honestly this course feeled like a glorified add. It told us stuff we can do and what advantages we have, but failed to  mention what disadvantages there are against similar solutions, thus giving us very narrow minded  approach.

There were n​ot enough oportunities to practive things in the Azure cloud in order to explore the theoretical concepts introduced in the course. Also, some of the links to the Azure learning environment (i.e concierge subscription) provided in the course instructions did not work, which made it difficult to do the excercises without a lot of searching around for fixes.
This course is more like a marketing series than cloud computing concepts, I recommend it if and only if you have previous knowledge of the cloud concepts and want to get a job using Azure only

Will have to review the whole thing again before taking the exam and make detailed notes, which is a bummer, I hoped going over the course once and spending the time would actually leave me knowing the topic quite well (which often is the case for other courses).

I​ am taking this class as part of the whole Azure fundementals certification, and eventually the Data Engineering certification. 

That said, I agree with those that said this does feel like a lot of advertising. That said, as someone that didn't know anything about cloud services, or Azure at all, I do have a better understanding of what it is, so I can participate in some of the conversations at work since we are probably going to be moving to the Azure service.

I did give this a 3 mostly because it was impossible to do any of the actual hands on practice. This sounds like it has been going on for months, from what I've see with other comments, and there was one person that said they were talking to the coursera support, but not being able to actually access the sandbox that was referenced and do the exerceises did impact some of the learning. 

If you are just curious about Azure, and don't plan to go for the cerfitication, don't take this class. If you are going to take the fundementals proctored exam, then know that this first class does seem like a lot of propeganda, but it also provides some basic explinations for those that are brand new to Azure and the cloud, and you just kind of have to get through it.
